‖X (I k).2 ω‖) μ := by\n        intro k\n        have h₈ : (I k).2 ∈ A := h₅ k\n        have h₉ : MemLp (X (I k).2) (2 * m) μ := memLp_X (I k).2 h₈\n        have h₁₀ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X (I k).2 ω‖) μ := by\n          have h₁₁ : (2 : ℕ) ≤ 2 * m := by\n            have h₁₂ : 0 < m := by\n              by_contra h\n              simp_all [Finset.prod_const]\n              <;> simp_all [Finset.card_eq_zero]\n              <;> aesop\n            have h₁₃ : 2 ≤ 2 * m := by\n              have h₁₄ : m ≥ 1 := by omega\n              nlinarith\n            exact h₁₃\n          have h₁₂ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X (I k).2 ω‖) μ := by\n            have h₁₃ : MemLp (X (I k).2) (2 : ℝ) μ := by\n              have h₁₄ : (2 : ℝ) ≤ (2 * m : ℝ) := by\n                norm_cast\n                <;> nlinarith\n              exact MemLp.of_le (by norm_num) h₉ (by linarith)\n            exact h₁₃.integrable_norm\n          exact h₁₂\n        exact h₁₀\n      have h₈ : ∀ (k : Fin m), Integrable (fun ω => ‖X (I k).1 ω‖ * ‖X (I k).2 ω‖) μ := by\n        intro k\n        have h₉ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X (I k).1 ω‖) μ := h₆ k\n        have h₁₀ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X (I k).2 ω‖) μ := h₇ k\n        have h₁₁ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X (I k).1 ω‖ * ‖X (I k).2 ω‖) μ := by\n          apply Integrable.mul h₉ h₁₀\n        exact h₁₁\n      have h₉ : Integrable (fun ω => ∏ k : Fin m, ‖X (I k).1 ω‖ * ‖X (I k).2 ω‖) μ := by\n        apply Finset.prod_integrable\n        intro k _\n        exact h₈ k\n      exact h₉\n    exact h₃",
      "\n    have h₁ : (fun ω => ∏ k : Fin m, ‖X (I k).1 ω‖ * ‖X (I k).2 ω‖) = ∏ k : Fin m, fun ω => ‖X (I k).1 ω‖ * ‖X (I k).2 ω‖ := by\n      ext ω\n      <;> simp [Finset.prod_const]\n      <;> congr\n      <;> ext\n      <;> simp\n    rw [h₁]\n    apply Finset.integrable_prod_of_nonneg\n    <;> intro i _\n    <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        apply MeasureTheory.integrable_of_mem_ℒp\n        <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            apply Continuous.norm\n            <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                exact continuous_const\n              })\n            <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                exact iIndepFun_X.toContinuousOn.1.fst\n              })\n          })\n      })\n    <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        positivity\n      })\n    <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        simp_all [mul_nonneg, norm_nonneg]\n      })\n    <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        intros\n        <;>\n        positivity\n      })",
      "\n    have h₁ : (∏ k, ‖X (I k).1 ‖) ∈ Lp (2 * m) μ := by sorry\n    have h₂ : (∏ k, ‖X (I k).2 ‖) ∈ Lp (2 * m) μ := by sorry\n    have h₃ : (∏ k, ‖X (I k).1 ‖ * ‖X (I k).2 ‖) ∈ Lp (2 * m) μ := by sorry\n    have h₄ : Integrable (fun ω ↦ ∏ k, ‖X (I k).1 ω‖ * ‖X (I k).2 ω‖) μ := by sorry\n    exact h₄\n  sorry",
      "",
      "More precisely, if `MemLp (X i) (2 * m) μ`, then `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m}(Ω, ℝ)`, so `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable.\n2. The product `∏_{k} ‖X (I k).1‖ * ‖X (I k).2‖` is of the form `∏_{k} (‖X i_k‖ * ‖X j_k‖)` where `i_k, j_k ∈ A`.\n   - To show integrability of this product, we need to control each term.\n3. Since each `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable, we can use Hölder's inequality or monotonicity of `L^p` spaces to deduce that lower powers of `‖X i‖` are also integrable. Specifically, for any `1 ≤ q ≤ 2m`, `‖X i‖^q ∈ L^1`. (This follows by noting that `‖X i‖^q ≤ 1 + ‖X i‖^{2m}` because `‖X i‖ ≥ 0`, and the RHS is integrable.)\n\n**Challenges:**\n- The product involves `2m` terms (`m` pairs of terms). We need to ensure that each term is integrable or can be controlled by the `L^{2m}` norm of the corresponding `X`.\n- A direct approach could be to bound each `‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖` term using the sum of their squares, but this seems complicated. \n- Instead, since each `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable, then for each `k`, both `‖X (I k).1‖` and `‖X (I k).2‖` are bounded in `L^{2m}`, hence also in `L^2` (because `L^{2m} → L^2` when `m ≥ 1`). Then each product `‖X (I k).1‖ * ‖X (I k).2‖` is in `L^1`, and so is their product. \n\nBut we have to be careful because `m` could be `0` (`m : ℕ`). If `m = 0`, the product is over an empty set, and is `1`, which is integrable (but the Lean statement requires `m : ℕ`). \n\nHowever, Lean's `Fin m` is empty when `m = 0`, so `∏ k : Fin 0, ... = 1`, which is trivially integrable. So we only need to check `m > 0`, but Lean will reconcile this automatically because it will consider `Fin 0` as empty.\n\nBut in the given problem, `I : Fin m → ι × ι`. If `m = 0`, then `I` is an empty function, and the product `∏ k : Fin m, ... = 1`. So the integrability reduces to `1` being integrable, which it is if `μ(Ω) < ∞`. But `μ` is a finite measure by `IsFiniteMeasure μ`, so `1` is integrable. \n\nHowever, checking Lean's type of `hI`, it's `I ∈ (A ×ˢ A)^m`, which is `I ∈ (Fin m → (A × A))` (`A ^ m`). But when `m = 0`, this is `I ∈ (Fin 0 → A × A)` which is `True` for the unique function on `Fin 0`, and the product is `1`. \n\nThus, for `m = 0`, the integrability is trivial. \n\nFor `m > 0`, we need to use that `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable and deduce that `‖X i‖^2` is integrable, so that each product term `‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖` is bounded by `(‖X i‖^2 + ‖X j‖^2)/2`, which is integrable.\n\nBut perhaps the easiest formal approach is to deduce that `‖X i‖^q` is integrable for any `q ≤ 2m`. \n\nSpecifically:\n1. Since `X i ∈ L^{2m}`, then `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m}`, so `‖X i‖^{2m} ∈ L^1`.\n2. For any `0 ≤ q ≤ 2m`, we have `‖X i‖^q ≤ 1 + ‖X i‖^{2m}`, because:\n   - If `‖X i‖ ≤ 1`, then `‖X i‖^q ≤ 1`.\n   - If `‖X i‖ > 1`, then `‖X i‖^q ≤ ‖X i‖^{2m}` since `q ≤ 2m` and `‖X i‖ > 1`.\nThus, `‖X i‖^q ≤ 1 + ‖X i‖^{2m}`, and since the RHS is integrable (`1` and `‖X i‖^{2m}` are integrable), then `‖X i‖^q ∈ L^1`. \n\nTherefore, for any `i ∈ A`, `‖X i‖` is in `L^q` for any `0 < q ≤ 2m`. \n\nBut we actually need `‖X i‖ ∈ L^2`, because each term is `‖X i‖`, and we are multiplying `2m` such terms (but grouped into pairs).\n\nBut perhaps we can directly observe that `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m}` implies that `‖X i‖^2 ∈ L^m`, because `(‖X i‖^2)^m = ‖X i‖^{2m} ∈ L^1`.\n\nBut it seems complicated to use this directly, as the product has terms like `‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖`, not `‖X i‖^2`. \n\nAlternative approach: Since for each pair `(i,j)` appearing in the product, we have `‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖ ≤ (‖X i‖^2 + ‖X j‖^2)/2`, but we have `m` pairs, this gives a bound by something like `(∑_{i,j} ‖X i‖^2 + ‖X j‖^2)^m`, but this seems messy.\n\nBut for our purpose, perhaps it is sufficient to note that `‖X i‖` is in `L^{2m}`, so in particular it is in `L^2`, because `2 ≤ 2m` when `m ≥ 1`.\n\nBut `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m}` is not directly true! Rather, we have `X i ∈ L^{2m}`, so `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m}`. \nAnd if `m ≥ 1`, then `2 ≤ 2m`, and thus `L^{2m}(Ω) ⊆ L^2(Ω)` (since `μ(Ω) < ∞`). \n\nBut in Lean, for `A : Finset ι`, `(A) ^ m` is `(Fin m → A)`, and for `m = 0`, this is the empty function, and for `m ≥ 1`, we have `Fin m` nonempty.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that for each `k`, `‖X (I k).1‖ * ‖X (I k).2‖ ≤ ‖X (I k).1‖^2 + ‖X (I k).2‖^2`, and each of these is in `L^m` because `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable.\n\nBut this seems too loose.\n\nAlternatively, since `m` is a natural number, perhaps it is better to use induction, but in Lean we need to avoid that unless forced.\n\nA better approach could be to use Hölder's inequality. Specifically:\n- The product of the `‖X i‖` is `≤ (∑ ‖X i‖^{p})^{n/p}`, but this does not directly help because we don't have bounds on `∑ ‖X i‖^p`. \n\nBut perhaps we can do something else. Since `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m}`, then for any `q ∈ [1, 2m]`, `‖X i‖ ∈ L^q` because `μ(Ω) < ∞` and `q ≤ 2m`.\n\nBut perhaps we should do this:\n1. For `m = 0`, the product is `1`, and since `μ` is finite, `1` is integrable.\n2. For `m ≥ 1`, then for any `i`, `X i ∈ L^{2m}`, and thus `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m}`.\n   - Since `2 ≤ 2m`, we have `L^{2m} ⊆ L^2`, because `μ(Ω) < ∞`, and thus `‖X i‖ ∈ L^2`.\n   - Therefore, `‖X i‖` is square integrable.\n   - Then, each term `‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖` is `≤ (‖X i‖^2 + ‖X j‖^2)/2`, and thus it is integrable.\n   - Since the product of `m` such terms is bounded by `2^m (∑ ‖X i‖^2)^m`, which is integrable because `(∑ ‖X i‖^2)^m` is integrable (since each `X i` is square integrable and `A` is finite).\n\nBut perhaps it's better to consider:\n1. Each `‖X i‖ ≤ 1 + ‖X i‖^{2m}` (as a function).\n2. Then, `∏ ‖X i‖ ≤ ∏ (1 + ‖X i‖^{2m})`, which is `≤ 2^{number of terms} (sum ‖X i‖^{2m})` (this is not true, but perhaps we can use `1 + x ≤ 2x` if `x ≥ 1`). \n\nThis seems too rough.\n\nBetter approach: \n1. When `m ≥ 1`, since `X i ∈ L^{2m}`, and `2 ≤ 2m`, `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable and `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m} ⊆ L^2` (`μ` finite).\n   - So `‖X i‖ ∈ L^2`.\n   - Therefore, `‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖ ∈ L^1`, because `(‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖)^2 = ‖X i‖^2 * ‖X j‖^2 ≤ (‖X i‖^2 + ‖X j‖^2)^2 / 4`, but more easily, because each `‖X i‖ ∈ L^2`, `‖X i‖^2` is integrable, and `(‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖)^2 = ‖X i‖² * ‖X j‖²`, and if `‖X i‖²` and `‖X j‖²` are integrable, then their product is `≤ (‖X i‖² + ‖X j‖²)^2 / 4`, and thus integrable (because `(‖X i‖²)^2 = ‖X i‖^{4}`, but `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable, and if `m ≥ 2`, then `4 ≤ 2m`, but perhaps not for `m = 1`).\n\nBut this path seems too complicated.\n\nAlternative approach: Since `m` is arbitrary, we can do a case distinction on `m = 0`:\n1. For `m = 0`, the product is `1` and is integrable.\n2. For `m ≥ 1`, each `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable, and since `μ(Ω) < ∞`, for each `i`, `‖X i‖ ∈ L^{2m} ⊆ L^2`, because `2 ≤ 2m` (as `m ≥ 1`). So `‖X i‖² ∈ L^1`, and thus each product `‖X i‖ * ‖X j‖` is in `L^1` (by Cauchy-Schwarz).\nBut `m` pairs multiplied together are not directly covered. Hmm.\n\nBut perhaps, for `m ≥ 1`, we can instead argue that since each `‖X i‖^{2m}` is integrable, then each `‖X i‖` is in `L^{2m}`, and hence for any `q ≤ 2m`, `‖X i‖^q` is in `L",
      "in Lean, `ψ(0, 1)` is `cos(π/3) * ∏ ≈",
      "\n    have h₁ : ∀ i ∈ A, Integrable (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2) μ := by\n      intro i hi\n      have h₂ : MemLp (X i) (2 * m) μ := memLp_X i hi\n      have h₃ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2) μ := by\n        -- Since X_i is in L^(2m), then |X_i|^2 is in L^m and hence integrable.\n        have h₄ : Integrable (fun ω : Ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2) μ := by\n          have h₅ : (2 : ℝ) ≤ (2 * m : ℝ) := by\n            norm_cast\n            have h₅₁ : 1 ≤ m := by\n              by_contra h₅₁\n              simp_all [Finset.prod_const]\n              <;>\n              (try cases m <;> simp_all [Finset.prod_const, Finset.card_univ, Finset.card_empty])\n              <;>\n              (try linarith)\n            nlinarith\n          -- Use the fact that ‖X_i‖^(2m) is integrable to deduce that ‖X_i‖^2 is integrable.\n          have h₆ : Integrable (fun ω : Ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ (2 * m)) μ := by\n            have h₇ : MemLp (X i) (2 * m) μ := memLp_X i hi\n            have h₈ : Integrable (fun ω : Ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ (2 * m)) μ := by\n              -- From the definition of L^(2m), we know that ‖X_i‖^(2m) is integrable.\n              exact h₇.integrable\n            exact h₈\n          -- Use the inequality ‖X_i‖^2 ≤ ‖X_i‖^(2m) to show that ‖X_i‖^2 is integrable.\n          have h₉ : (fun ω : Ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2) ≤ᵐ[μ] (fun ω : Ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ (2 * m)) := by\n            have h₁₀ : ∀ ω : Ω, ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2 ≤ ‖X i ω‖ ^ (2 * m) := by\n              intro ω\n              by_cases h₁₁ : ‖X i ω‖ = 0\n              · simp_all [h₁₁]\n                <;>\n                (try norm_num)\n                <;>\n                (try positivity)\n              · have h₁₂ : 1 ≤ ‖X i ω‖ := by\n                  by_contra h₁₂\n                  have h₁₃ : ‖X i ω‖ < 1 := by linarith\n                  have h₁₄ : ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2 < 1 := by\n                    have h₁₅ : 0 ≤ ‖X i ω‖ := by positivity\n                    have h₁₆ : ‖X i ω‖ < 1 := by linarith\n                    have h₁₇ : ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2 < 1 := by\n                      nlinarith\n                    exact h₁₇\n                  have h₁₈ : ‖X i ω‖ ^ (2 * m) < 1 := by\n                    have h₁₉ : 0 ≤ ‖X i ω‖ := by positivity\n                    have h₂₀ : ‖X i ω‖ < 1 := by linarith\n                    have h₂₁ : ‖X i ω‖ ^ (2 * m) < 1 := by\n                      calc\n                        ‖X i ω‖ ^ (2 * m) < 1 ^ (2 * m) := by\n                          exact pow_lt_pow_of_lt_left h₂₀ (by positivity) (by\n                            have h₂₂ : 0 < 2 * m := by\n                              have h₂₃ : 1 ≤ m := by\n                                by_contra h₂₃\n                                simp_all [Finset.prod_const]\n                                <;>\n                                (try cases m <;> simp_all [Finset.prod_const, Finset.card_univ, Finset.card_empty])\n                                <;>\n                                (try linarith)\n                              nlinarith\n                            positivity)\n                        _ = 1 := by simp\n                    exact h₂₁\n                  have h₂₂ : ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2 ≥ 0 := by positivity\n                  have h₂₃ : ‖X i ω‖ ^ (2 * m) ≥ 0 := by positivity\n                  linarith\n                have h₁₃ : (1 : ℝ) ≤ ‖X i ω‖ := by linarith\n                have h₁₄ : (2 : ℕ) ≤ 2 * m := by\n                  have h₁₅ : 1 ≤ m := by\n                    by_contra h₁₅\n                    simp_all [Finset.prod_const]\n                    <;>\n                    (try cases m <;> simp_all [Finset.prod_const, Finset.card_univ, Finset.card_empty])\n                    <;>\n                    (try linarith)\n                  have h₁₆ : (2 : ℕ) ≤ 2 * m := by\n                    nlinarith\n                  exact h₁₆\n                have h₁₅ : (‖X i ω‖ : ℝ) ^ 2 ≤ (‖X i ω‖ : ℝ) ^ (2 * m) := by\n                  have h₁₆ : (1 : ℝ) ≤ (‖X i ω‖ : ℝ) := by exact_mod_cast h₁₃\n                  have h₁₇ : (2 : ℕ) ≤ 2 * m := by exact_mod_cast h₁₄\n                  calc\n                    (‖X i ω‖ : ℝ) ^ 2 ≤ (‖X i ω‖ : ℝ) ^ 2 := by linarith\n                    _ ≤ (‖X i ω‖ : ℝ) ^ (2 * m) := by\n                      exact pow_le_pow_right (by linarith) (by\n                        have h₁₈ : (2 : ℕ) ≤ 2 * m := by exact_mod_cast h₁₄\n                        omega)\n                exact_mod_cast h₁₅\n            exact eventually_of_forall h₁₀\n          -- Use the fact that ‖X_i‖^(2m) is integrable to deduce that ‖X_i‖^2 is integrable.\n          have h₁₀ : Integrable (fun ω : Ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2) μ := by\n            refine' Integrable.of_nonneg_of_le (fun ω => by positivity) h₉ _\n            exact h₆\n          exact h₁₀\n        exact h₄\n      exact h₃\n    have h₂ : ∀ (i : ι), Integrable (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2) μ → Integrable (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖) μ := by\n      intro i hi\n      -- Use the fact that ‖X_i‖^2 is integrable to deduce that ‖X_i‖ is integrable.\n      have h₃ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖) μ := by\n        -- Since ‖X_i‖^2 is integrable, ‖X_i‖ is also integrable because ‖X_i‖ ≤ ‖X_i‖^2 + 1.\n        have h₄ : (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖) ≤ᵐ[μ] (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2 + 1) := by\n          have h₅ : ∀ ω : Ω, ‖X i ω‖ ≤ ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2 + 1 := by\n            intro ω\n            have h₆ : 0 ≤ ‖X i ω‖ := norm_nonneg (X i ω)\n            nlinarith [sq_nonneg (‖X i ω‖ - 1)]\n          exact eventually_of_forall h₅\n        have h₅ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2 + 1) μ := by\n          -- ‖X_i‖^2 + 1 is integrable because ‖X_i‖^2 is integrable and 1 is integrable.\n          have h₆ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖ ^ 2) μ := hi\n          have h₇ : Integrable (fun ω => (1 : ℝ)) μ := by\n            -- 1 is integrable because the measure space is finite.\n            exact integrable_const\n          -- The sum of two integrable functions is integrable.\n          exact h₆.add h₇\n        -- Since ‖X_i‖ ≤ ‖X_i‖^2 + 1 and ‖X_i‖^2 + 1 is integrable, ‖X_i‖ is integrable.\n        have h₆ : Integrable (fun ω => ‖X i ω‖) μ := by\n          refine' Integrable.of_nonneg_of_le (fun ω => by positivity) h₄ _\n          exact h₅\n        exact h₆\n      exact h₃\n    sorry",
